<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="37" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1002,2036]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,328,1226,1252]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Integument ventrocaudally areolate, dorsally papillate. Dorsum with seven or eight muscle attachment plates in males and females, respectively. Cx-I+II medially not fused. Excretory pore smooth. Capitulum with short rostrum; P- 
<number box="[552,567,1301,1327]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="4.0">4</number>
shorter than P- 
<number box="[757,771,1301,1327]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
, with the two well developed ventral tubercles close to each other, each bearing peg-like and at the tip truncated setae, the proximal one larger located in the proximal part, the distal one minor, located slightly anterior to the centre of the segment. Leg ambulacrum with claw blade well protruding and dorsal and ventral clawlets.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1002,2036]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,152,1223]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,1450,1476]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Description.</emphasis>
Integument ventrocaudally with fine denticles arranged in a hexagonal pattern; these denticles laterally and caudally inflating to form small rounded papillae; these papillae regularly-arranged, nowhere fused to form lines or irregular structures, completely covering the dorsal surface. Dorsum with seven or eight muscle attachment plates in males and females, respectively, following the terminology of 
<bibRefCitation author="Bader" box="[151,531,1600,1626]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" refString="Bader, C. &amp; Sepasgozarian, H. (1980 a) Wassermilben (Acari, Prostigmata, Hydrachnellae) aus dem Iran. 11. Mitteilung. Sperchon (Mixosperchon) afzalipouri nov. spec. Journal of Entomological Society of Iran, 5 (1,2), 35 - 55." type="journal article" year="1980" yearSuffix="a">
Bader &amp; Sepasgozarian (
<number box="[448,510,1600,1626]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="1980.0">1980</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
from anterior to posterior: medially, (
<number box="[985,997,1600,1626]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="1.0">1</number>
) large, round praefrontalia, (
<number box="[1344,1360,1600,1626]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
) large plates consisting of fused postfrontalia, postocularia and dc- 
<number box="[862,872,1637,1663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="1.0">1</number>
, (
<number box="[895,910,1637,1663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
) dc- 
<number box="[964,978,1637,1663]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
fused to an unpaired medial platelet in male, and close to each other but not fused in female, (
<number box="[797,813,1674,1700]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="4.0">4</number>
) dc- 
<number box="[869,882,1674,1700]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
large and close to each other but not fused, (
<number box="[1411,1426,1674,1700]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="5.0">5</number>
) dc- 
<number box="[192,208,1712,1738]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="4.0">4</number>
, smaller, but more distanced from each other than dc- 
<number box="[882,896,1712,1738]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
, and, laterally, (
<number box="[1096,1144,1712,1738]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6–8</number>
) relatively large, round platelets dl- 
<number box="[295,329,1749,1775]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1-3</number>
located at the levels of interspace dc- 
<number box="[783,793,1749,1775]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[803,819,1749,1775]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
, dc- 
<number box="[873,886,1749,1775]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
, and interspace dc- 
<number box="[1118,1131,1749,1775]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[1141,1156,1749,1775]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="4.0">4</number>
, respectively (
<figureCitation box="[1328,1422,1749,1775]" captionStart="FIGURE 2 A – D" captionStartId="4.[151,255,1971,1995]" captionTargetBox="[234,1355,207,1951]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[212,1390,197,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2 A – D. Sperchon oezkani sp. nov. (A – C = male, D = female): A = coxal and genital field; B = idiosoma, dorsal view; C = chelicera; D = capitulum. Scale bars = 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196104/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
Fig. 
<number box="[1384,1401,1749,1775]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
B
</figureCitation>
). Ventral view: Cx-I+II medially close to each other, but not fused (
<figureCitation box="[924,1019,1786,1812]" captionStart="FIGURE 2 A – D" captionStartId="4.[151,255,1971,1995]" captionTargetBox="[234,1355,207,1951]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[212,1390,197,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2 A – D. Sperchon oezkani sp. nov. (A – C = male, D = female): A = coxal and genital field; B = idiosoma, dorsal view; C = chelicera; D = capitulum. Scale bars = 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196104/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
Fig. 
<number box="[979,995,1786,1812]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). Cx-III without a medial glandular opening (Cxgl- 
<number box="[335,351,1824,1850]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="4.0">4</number>
). Ac- 
<number box="[422,455,1824,1850]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1-2</number>
longish, Ac- 
<number box="[613,626,1824,1850]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
roundish. Posterior part of the venter with well-developed unpaired postgenital platelet and further three pairs of ventralia. Excretory pore smooth. Capitulum (
<figureCitation box="[1212,1303,1861,1887]" captionStart="FIGURE 2 A – D" captionStartId="4.[151,255,1971,1995]" captionTargetBox="[234,1355,207,1951]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[212,1390,197,1965]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2 A – D. Sperchon oezkani sp. nov. (A – C = male, D = female): A = coxal and genital field; B = idiosoma, dorsal view; C = chelicera; D = capitulum. Scale bars = 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196104/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
Fig. 
<number box="[1266,1281,1861,1887]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
D
</figureCitation>
) with short rostrum; palps (
<figureCitation box="[334,412,1898,1924]" captionStart="FIGURE 3 A – G. A – D" captionStartId="5.[151,256,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[192,1423,231,1927]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[176,1424,194,1940]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3 A – G. A – D. Sperchon oezkani sp. nov. (A – B, D = male, C = female): A = palp, laterall view; B – C = palp, medial view; D = IV-Leg- 4 – 6. E – G Sperchon afzalipouri Bader &amp; Sepasgozarian (E – F = male, G = female): E = palp, lateral view; F = palp, medial view; G = P- 4. Scale bars = 100 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196105/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
Figs. 
<number box="[399,412,1898,1924]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A-C); P- 
<number box="[519,529,1898,1924]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="1.0">1</number>
without dorsal seta; P- 
<number box="[797,811,1898,1924]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
distoventrally with a long projection at its tip bearing three fine setae, one long and two short; P- 
<number box="[661,674,1936,1962]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
bearing about 
<number box="[851,880,1936,1962]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="10.0">10</number>
fine setae and several short hairs, all restricted to the dorsal part; P- 
<number box="[389,403,1973,1999]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="4.0">4</number>
shorter than P- 
<number box="[586,600,1973,1999]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" value="3.0">3</number>
, with the two well developed ventral tubercles close to each other, each bearing peg-like, at the tip truncated setae, the proximal larger one located in the proximal part, the distal minor one located slightly anterior to the centre of the segment; P- 
<number box="[978,992,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="38" value="5.0">5</number>
short, with strong distal claws; Leg segments slender, III-/IV-L with a few short, simple dorsal setae; ambulacrum with claw blade well protruding, bearing a long dorsal and a shorter ventral clawlet.
</paragraph>
